`ctx-core` is a dependency-free shared kernel: it exists so `ctx-scan` and `ctx-context` (and any future tool) share one canonical answer to two questions — "is this path accessible?" and "what's the on-disk hash-sidecar schema?" — instead of maintaining divergent copies. Depending on this crate gets you pure, panic-free functions; it defines no crate-wide error type, so callers wrap results into their own error enums.

The two submodules are independent (no cross-file coupling) but share a status as single-source-of-truth per ADR-023: any tool reimplementing secret/binary detection or hash-sidecar parsing instead of importing from here is a bug, specifically flagged as a secret-exfiltration risk for `access`. `access.rs` is the deny-by-default gate (secret > binary > ignored priority, ignore-check deferred to caller) used before any read/summarize. `hashtree.rs` is the `DirNode`/`hex_hash` schema for `.context/<dir>/hashes.json`, consumed by `ctx-scan` as writer and `ctx-context` as reader — the `f:`/`d:` child-key prefix convention and SHA-256 hex format must match exactly on both sides or freshness detection silently breaks.

`lib.rs` only re-exports `access` and `hashtree`; no logic lives at the crate root.